Routes and Controller

7 steps

In Back End Development, there is no preconfigured structure waiting for us; instead, we have the freedom to craft our own folders and files. This inherent flexibility is one of the defining aspects of Back End Development, granting us complete autonomy over the organization of our codebase.

We will construct a mock blog application that mirrors the typical setup of a back end application. Within our 'app.js', the central file of our server, we often encounter a myriad of routes and logic scattered throughout. In practical back end projects, the number of API routes can swell into the tens or even hundreds, necessitating an efficient means of organization.

We will delve into the art of structuring routes by categorizing them into separate files based on their specific functionality. Additionally, we will introduce a "Controller" folder. This dedicated space will house all the intricate application logic responsible for managing the inner workings of the back end. We will create three primary routes, each of which will have its own set of routes and corresponding controllers.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • ExpressJS

Learning Outcomes

By the end of your learning, you will be able to

  • Explore the concept of creating a mock blog application as a practical use case for Back End development.
  • Define the concept of primary routing, which represents the main sections or features of your application.
  • Explain how primary routes can have their sub-routes for handling specific functionalities.
  • Split routes into multiple files based on their functionality
  • Create controller files and structure them to handle different aspects of the Back End application.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 7

  • Step 1: Setting Up Our Workspace

    To start, open the coding workspace of your choice. In our case, we will be using VS Code. Open your terminal in your code editor and ensure that the current working directory is the root folder which we created previously (StackUp-BackEnd-ExpressJS-Part-II).

    Next, in the code editor, open up the terminal and enter the following commands.

    mkdir routes-controllers
cd routes-controllers
npm install express morgan body-parser

    We just entered 3 commands. First, using mkdir, it creates a directory within our root directory. The second command changes the current working directory to the new folder we have created. The last command will install the following 3 packages: Express, Morgan, and Body Parser. These will be the only dependencies needed. 

  • Step 2: Public Folder

    In Express, we will need a place to store our files that can be accessible to the public. For example, CSS files, images, videos and more. In our project folder (routes-controllers), create a new folder called public.

    You can use this folder to allow your files to be publicly accessible. Within this folder, create a new file called public.txt. Add the following text to the file: This is made public intentionally.

    We just created a new file in the public folder, which will be helpful when you are debugging to determine if your public folder is recognised by your back end.

  • Step 3: app.js

    We will now create the entry file for the backend application. In the routes-controllers folder, create a new file app.js. Once you have created the file, open it and add the following code below. 

    const express = require('express');
const morgan = require('morgan');

const app = express();
const port = 3001;

app.use(express.static('public'));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

const server = app.listen(port, () => {
    console.log("Server listening");
});

app.use(morgan('dev'));

app.use('/auth', require('./routes/authHandling'));
app.use('/user', require('./routes/userHandling'));
app.use('/blogs', require('./routes/blogHandling'));

app.use((req, res) => {
    res.status(404).send("Page not found");
})
    JavaScript

    We begin by importing the necessary modules. The express module in line 1 is crucial for creating an Express app.

    Here, we create an instance of the Express app using the express() function (line 4). Additionally, we establish a constant named port in line 6, and this constant is set to 3001, signifying the port where our server will listen for incoming requests.

    As we proceed, we integrate middleware functions into the Express app. Line 14 employs morgan('dev') to apply logging middleware, which will log incoming requests and their details to the console.

    Static files, such as images, stylesheets, and JavaScript files, are typically served from a public directory. We use the express.static('public') middleware (line 7) to serve static files from the 'public' directory.

    Lines 16 to 18 represent the primary routes. Any routes starting with “/auth” will be redirected to the file “./routes/authHandling” (line 16). The same logic will apply for the subsequent primary routes. In a decent scale project, there will be multiple routes needed for various purpose and functionality.

    If none of the routes the server has received falls within the primary routings, we will use lines 20 to 22 to handle and send a status 404.

  • Step 4: Routes

    Within our project folder routes-controllers, create a new folder called routes. Your project folder should now contain 3 folders (node_modules, public and routes).

    In this step, we will be creating 3 new route files, one for each primary routes. Within the routes folder, create a new file called authHandling.js and add the code shown below. 

    const router = require('express').Router();

const authController = require('../controllers/authController');

router.post('/register', (req, res) => authController.register_user(req, res));
router.post('/login', (req, res) => authController.login(req, res));
router.get('/test', (req, res) => authController.test(req, res));

module.exports = router;
    JavaScript

    The code above represents the 3 subroutes that belong to the /auth primary route. This means that the routes relating to authentication are shown like this: 

    1. POST /auth/register
    2. POST /auth/login
    3. GET /auth/test

    Those are the routes that will be associated with the primary routes. We have also broken up the way we handle the incoming request by placing each code file in their own logic. For example in line 5, whenever the user submit a POST /auth/register request, their request will be routed towards the authController and using the register_user function in the authController file. Do note that we have yet to create the authController file. That is essentially how we are going to neatly organise our routes. In one look we are able to identify which route naming is available to use and we can also see the subroutes at a glance.

    Next, with the login in mind, we will also create similar files within the routes folder. Create a new file called blogHandling.js and add the following code. 

    const router = require('express').Router();

const blogController = require('../controllers/blogController');

router.post('/', (req, res) => blogController.create_new_blog(req, res));
router.put('/id/:blog_id', (req, res) => blogController.update_blog_by_id(req, res));
router.delete('/id/:blog_id', (req, res) => blogController.delete_blog_by_id(req, res));
router.get('/id/:blog_id', (req, res) => blogController.get_blog_by_id(req, res));
router.get('/', (req, res) => blogController.get_all_blogs(req, res));
router.get('/test', (req, res) => blogController.test(req, res));

module.exports = router;
    JavaScript

    The code snippet above will be similar to the authHandling.js file. We will be using this file to show how similar grouping each routing can be.

    Within the routes folder, create a new file called userHandling.js and add the following code as shown below. 

    const router = require('express').Router();

const userController = require('../controllers/userController');

router.get('/profile/id/:user_id', (req, res) => userController.get_user_profile_by_id(req, res));
router.put('/profile/id/:user_id', (req, res) => userController.update_user_profile_by_id(req, res));
router.get('/test', (req, res) => userController.test(req, res));

module.exports = router;
    JavaScript

    In lines 5 and 6, there is a :user_id. user_id is the name of the parameter expected for the sub routes. You may notice that in line 7 in userHandling.js, we have a route GET “/user/test”. We will be using it to test whether the endpoint is accessible. Since we are segregating the files into a grouped routings file, we will need to ensure that the routings will be handled accordingly. 

  • Step 5: Controllers

    Within our project folder, create a new folder called controllers. Now we will be creating our controller files. Our controller files are to manage the incoming requests our server receives. A lot of the application logic will be shown under the controllers folder.

    Within the controllers folder, create a new file called authController.js and add the code as shown below. 

    const register_user = (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: "register_user"
        });
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message });
    }
}

const login = (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: "login"
        });
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message });
    }
}

const test = (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: "test"
        });
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message });
    }
}

module.exports = {
    register_user,
    login,
    test
}
    JavaScript

    In the code snippet above, there are 3 functions that is meant to have varying purposes. In this request, we will send back a status 200 just to view how the routes connect with each other. You may also notice that in lines 2, 12 and 22 we are using a try-catch statement. Usually we wrap our functions within these statements to catch any error that could arise from our backend application logic.

    Lastly from lines 31 to 35, we will export the 3 functions. This will allow any files referencing the authController.js file to use the functions within the file. For example, line 3 of authHandling.js references the file and lines 5 to 7 use those 3 functions.

    Next, we will be creating a new file for the blog controller. Within the controllers folder, create a new file called blogController.js. Add the code below. 

    const create_new_blog = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: "create_new_blog"
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message })
    }
}
const update_blog_by_id = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: "update_blog_by_id"
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message })
    }
}
const delete_blog_by_id = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: "delete_blog_by_id"
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message })
    }
}
const get_blog_by_id = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: `get_blog_by_id ${req.params.blog_id}`
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message })
    }
}
const get_all_blogs = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: "get_all_blogs"
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message })
    }
}
const test = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: "test"
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error })
    }
}

module.exports = {
    create_new_blog,
    update_blog_by_id,
    delete_blog_by_id,
    get_blog_by_id,
    get_all_blogs,
    test
}
    JavaScript

    Similar to the auth controller file, we have created 6 functions for the 6 subroutes of the “blog” primary route. In line 31, we can obtain the blog_id parameter by using req.params.blog_id.

    Lastly, create a new file called userController.js within the controllers folder. In this file, add the code shown below. 

    const get_user_profile_by_id = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: `get_user_profile_by_id ${req.params.user_id}`
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message })
    }
}

const update_user_profile_by_id = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: `update_user_profile_by_id ${req.params.user_id}`
        })
    } catch (error) {
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message })
    }
}

const test = async (req, res) => {
    try {
        throw new Error("test error: this error is deliberately thrown to test the error handling")
        return res.status(200).send({
            message: "test"
        })
    } catch (error) {
        console.log(error)
        return res.status(500).json({ message: error.message })
    }
}

module.exports = {
    get_user_profile_by_id,
    update_user_profile_by_id,
    test
}
    JavaScript

    If we look at line 23, we deliberately issue an error. This is to simulate an instance if we want to do data or error handling. By doing so, we are able to trigger the catch block as shown in line 27.

    From the controller files we have created above, authController.js, blogController.js and userController.js, notice that every function will take in 2 arguments called req and res. “req” stands for request and it embodies the data that contains the request from the front end. The “res” stands for responses and that is how we are able to send the backend response to the front end.

    Taking userController.js as an example, you can notice that we will use res.status() in lines 7, 17 and 29 to set the status of the request. We will also use the .json() method or the .send() method to send back any payload to the front end.

  • Step 6: Running our Server Script

    At this point, your file structure should look like this. It is important that you check the spelling of your files to ensure this step proceeds smoothly. 

    We will now run the script app.js. In your terminal, ensure that your current working directory is on routes-controllers, the folder to which we have added our packages and app.js.

    Use the command node app.js to kick-start your server application.

    We have just created our very own server which will serve the frontend components to the front end. Now, in your internet browser, enter http://localhost:3001/auth/test in your browser.

    ⚠️ For users of Google Cloud Shell, in the top bar, click on the icon for web preview and ensure the port number is 3001. In the new tab, append /auth/test to the URL.

    Your browser should show the following output.

    As part of the deliverable, you will also need to visit /user/test which should deliberately return an error.
